text.tspan: . There is a need for a permanent
global monitoring network to ensure that atmospheric Hg concentration
trends may be established unambiguously. Data from such a network
could also be used for model testing and evaluation, and enhance
confidence in the results of modelling evaluations of future emission
. There currently are no indicators that link together Hg emissions
with health impacts via seafood consumption.Commercial marine fish account
for >90% of mercury exposure in the U.S.), mainly from pelagic marine fish
(tuna). This means that human exposures reflect the global burden of mercury
in addition to local sources and resulting contamination in regional water
bodies. Better data on the geographic origins of seafood being consumed by
different populations is critical for establishing the link between changes in Hg
emissions, atmospheric deposition and concentration in fish.
Hemisphere, especially south of 40–60°N, is relatively unexplored territory
with respect to Hg. The next generation monitoring absolutely must address
this gap, especially if global patterns of Hg are to be understood. Monitoring
at these sites is useful for the study of long-range atmospheric transport
patterns, and how these are influenced by large scale climatic variations.
current technologies and methods require ishigh
investment and running costs that cannot necessarily be used in a
continuous monitoring program, especially at remote locations. The
development of simpler and less expensive methods is needed. The next
generation of air quality monitoring will require a two-fold effort, investment
in developing new low cost sensors and an expansion in the number of
permanent Hg monitoring sites worldwide, especially in the southern
hemisphere and in those regions whose economies are growing the fastest.
